<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-876-488  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 876 488.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  Nov 13 1989 v11 n46 pS20(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Server-based and peer-to-peer LAN designs. (technical descriptionof different network types)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Needleman, Raphael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Two basic types of microcomputer local-area networks areserver-based networks, in which a dedicated central computershares files and resources among workstations, and peer-to-peernetworks, where each computer shares data and resources withothers on an equal basis.andP;  Servers include file servers, which actas remote hard disks and monitor access privileges; print servers,which let network users share output devices and have extra RAMmemory to 'spool' printer jobs; and such communications servers asmodem servers, fax gateways, and mainframe gateways.andP;  Peer-to-peernetworks are much easier to set up than server-based networks andcost far less; most are designed to support small groups of underten users, while server-based networks can often support hundredsof users.andP;  A peer-to-peer network may be purchased one workstationat a time and is an effective solution for small-scale needs.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Local Area NetworksFile ServersNetwork ArchitectureTutorialConfigurationMicrocomputers.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Two kinds of LANs. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>